This is a problem I find genuinely exciting because most attempts land in one of two traps: they model *notation* (what you'd write on paper) or they model *audio* (what you'd hear). Neither captures what a musician actually *thinks*. Let me try to hit that conceptual layer.

## The Core Tension

Music is simultaneously **horizontal** (melody unfolds in time) and **vertical** (harmony stacks in the moment). It's also **hierarchical** — notes form motifs, motifs form phrases, phrases form sections — and the hierarchies don't align neatly. A melodic phrase might deliberately cross a bar line. A harmonic progression might fight the metric accent. These *misalignments* are where musical interest lives.

Most data models flatten this into a timeline of events (MIDI) or a tree of containers (MusicXML). I want something closer to how music theory actually works: **intervals matter more than absolute pitches**, **rhythm is proportional not absolute**, and **chords have functions, not just spellings**.

Here's where I'd land, in Dart since that's your world, but the ideas are structural:

```dart
// ─── Pitch: not frequency, not MIDI number, but musical identity ───
// C# and Db are the same key on a piano but different musical thoughts.
// This matters for spelling chords, reading intervals, voice leading.

enum NoteName { c, d, e, f, g, a, b }

enum Accidental { doubleFlat, flat, natural, sharp, doubleSharp }

class PitchClass {
  final NoteName name;
  final Accidental accidental;
  const PitchClass(this.name, [this.accidental = Accidental.natural]);

  /// Semitones from C, mod 12. Two PitchClasses can have the same
  /// semitone value but different identities (enharmonic equivalents).
  int get semitones => /* ... */;

  /// This is the key operation: interval *from* another pitch class.
  Interval intervalFrom(PitchClass other) => /* ... */;
}

class Pitch {
  final PitchClass pitchClass;
  final int octave; // scientific pitch notation: middle C = C4
  const Pitch(this.pitchClass, this.octave);

  /// Transpose by an interval. Returns a new Pitch, correctly spelled.
  Pitch transpose(Interval interval) => /* ... */;
}
```

Nothing surprising yet. But here's where it starts to matter:

```dart
// ─── Intervals as first-class citizens ───
// A melody *is* its intervals. Transpose it and nothing changes musically.
// An interval has both a numeric size (3rd, 5th) and a quality (major, minor).

enum IntervalQuality { diminished, minor, perfect, major, augmented }

class Interval {
  final IntervalQuality quality;
  final int number; // 1 = unison, 2 = second, ... 8 = octave
  const Interval(this.quality, this.number);

  int get semitones => /* derived from quality + number */;

  Interval invert() => /* octave complement: M3 ↔ m6, P4 ↔ P5 */;

  /// Compound intervals: stack two intervals
  Interval operator +(Interval other) => /* ... */;
}
```

Now the first real design decision — **rhythm as ratio, not duration**:

```dart
// ─── Rhythm: proportional, not absolute ───
// A quarter note isn't "500ms". It's "one beat" in common time,
// "one third of a beat" in 6/8. Tempo is a separate concern entirely.

class Duration {
  /// Fraction of a whole note. Quarter = 1/4, dotted half = 3/4.
  /// Using Rational to avoid floating point — rhythm is exact.
  final Rational fraction;
  const Duration(this.fraction);

  static const whole    = Duration(Rational(1, 1));
  static const half     = Duration(Rational(1, 2));
  static const quarter  = Duration(Rational(1, 4));
  static const eighth   = Duration(Rational(1, 8));

  Duration dotted() => Duration(fraction * Rational(3, 2));

  /// Tuplets: divide this duration into n equal parts
  Duration tuplet(int n) => Duration(fraction * Rational(2, n));
}

class TimeSignature {
  final int beats;
  final int beatUnit; // 4 = quarter gets the beat, 8 = eighth, etc.
  const TimeSignature(this.beats, this.beatUnit);

  /// The musical weight of each beat position — this is what makes
  /// 3/4 feel different from 6/8 even when they have the same total duration.
  List<MetricWeight> get accentPattern => /* ... */;
}
```

Now the core musical atoms and how they compose. This is where I spent the most thought:

```dart
// ─── The Music type: an algebra of sequential and parallel composition ───
// Inspired by Euterpea's elegance but with harmonic awareness bolted on.

sealed class Music {
  Duration get duration;
}

/// A single sounding note — pitch, duration, and performance qualities.
class Note extends Music {
  final Pitch pitch;
  final Duration duration;
  final Articulation articulation;  // staccato, legato, accent, etc.
  final Dynamic dynamic;            // ppp through fff
  const Note(this.pitch, this.duration, {
    this.articulation = Articulation.normal,
    this.dynamic = Dynamic.mf,
  });
}

/// Silence is musical too.
class Rest extends Music {
  final Duration duration;
  const Rest(this.duration);
}

/// Sequential composition: one thing, then another.
/// A melody is a Seq of Notes. A whole piece is a Seq of sections.
class Seq extends Music {
  final List<Music> children;
  const Seq(this.children);

  Duration get duration =>
      children.fold(Duration.zero, (sum, m) => sum + m.duration);
}

/// Parallel composition: things happening simultaneously.
/// A chord is a Par of Notes. An orchestral score is a Par of parts.
class Par extends Music {
  final List<Music> children;
  const Par(this.children);

  /// Duration = longest child. The others are "padded" with silence.
  Duration get duration =>
      children.map((m) => m.duration).reduce(max);
}

/// Here's where it gets interesting: transformations as first-class music.
/// "Play this melody backwards" IS the music, not a preprocessing step.
class Transform extends Music {
  final Music source;
  final MusicalTransform transform;
  const Transform(this.source, this.transform);

  Duration get duration => transform.transformedDuration(source.duration);
}
```

The transformation type is where the algebraic structure really shines:

```dart
// ─── Transformations: the operations a composer actually thinks in ───

sealed class MusicalTransform {
  Music apply(Music source);
  Duration transformedDuration(Duration original);
}

/// Transposition: shift everything by an interval.
class Transpose extends MusicalTransform {
  final Interval interval;
  Transpose(this.interval);
  // Duration unchanged. Every pitch shifts.
}

/// Inversion: flip intervals around an axis pitch.
/// A rising major third becomes a falling major third.
class Invert extends MusicalTransform {
  final Pitch axis;
  Invert(this.axis);
}

/// Retrograde: reverse in time. Bach loved this.
class Retrograde extends MusicalTransform {}

/// Augmentation/Diminution: stretch or compress time.
class ScaleTime extends MusicalTransform {
  final Rational factor; // 2 = augmentation (twice as slow), 1/2 = diminution
  ScaleTime(this.factor);
}

/// The real power: transformations compose.
class ComposeTransforms extends MusicalTransform {
  final List<MusicalTransform> transforms;
  ComposeTransforms(this.transforms);
  // Apply in sequence. Retrograde + Invert = retrograde inversion.
}
```

Now the layer most representations miss entirely — **harmonic context**:

```dart
// ─── Harmony: chords have *function*, not just spelling ───

class Scale {
  final PitchClass root;
  final ScaleType type; // major, minor, dorian, mixolydian, etc.
  const Scale(this.root, this.type);

  /// The available pitch classes, in order.
  List<PitchClass> get degrees => /* derived from root + type's interval pattern */;

  /// Build a chord on a scale degree. This is how musicians think:
  /// "the V chord in C major" not "a G major triad."
  Chord chord(int degree, {ChordExtension extension = ChordExtension.triad}) =>
      /* ... */;
}

/// A chord knows both its spelling AND its function.
class Chord {
  final PitchClass root;
  final ChordQuality quality; // major, minor, diminished, augmented, dominant7, etc.
  final HarmonicFunction? function; // tonic, predominant, dominant — context-dependent

  /// The actual pitch classes, voiced in a particular way.
  /// Voicing matters: C-E-G and E-G-C are the "same chord"
  /// but different musical textures.
  final List<PitchClass> voicing;
}

enum HarmonicFunction {
  tonic,        // home, stability, resolution
  predominant,  // motion, preparing the dominant
  dominant,     // tension, demanding resolution
}
```

And here's the thing I keep circling back to — the part that most excites me and where my confidence thins out. Music is fundamentally about **tension and release**. A dominant seventh *wants* to resolve. A suspension *aches* to step down. A crescendo *builds* toward something. Can we make that structural?

```dart
// ─── Tension: the thing music is actually about ───
// This is speculative. I'm not sure it belongs in the data model vs.
// being an analysis layer on top. But I think it's worth trying.

class TensionAnnotation {
  /// 0.0 = complete rest/resolution. 1.0 = maximum tension.
  /// This isn't a single number in real music — it's multi-dimensional
  /// (harmonic tension, rhythmic tension, dynamic tension, registral tension).
  /// But even a single axis captures something real.
  final Map<TensionDimension, double> tensions;

  /// What is this tension *pointing toward*? A dominant chord's tension
  /// points toward its resolution. A crescendo points toward its peak.
  final Music? impliedResolution;
}

enum TensionDimension {
  harmonic,   // dissonance, distance from tonic
  rhythmic,   // syncopation, cross-rhythm, metric displacement
  dynamic,    // volume trajectory (crescendo = building tension)
  registral,  // extreme high/low registers = tension
  timbral,    // harsh vs. smooth
}
```

## How It Composes — A Real Example

Here's what writing music in this system looks like:

```dart
// "Twinkle Twinkle" — but described as a musician would think about it
final key = Scale(PitchClass(NoteName.c), ScaleType.major);
final q = Duration.quarter;
final h = Duration.half;

final melody = Seq([
  // "Twinkle twinkle" — note the repeated tonic, then the leap to 5th
  Note(key.pitch(1, 4), q), Note(key.pitch(1, 4), q),
  Note(key.pitch(5, 4), q), Note(key.pitch(5, 4), q),
  Note(key.pitch(6, 4), q), Note(key.pitch(6, 4), q),
  Note(key.pitch(5, 4), h),
]);

// Harmonize: I – I – IV – I (tonic, tonic, predominant, tonic)
final harmony = Seq([
  key.chord(1).asMusic(h),
  key.chord(4).asMusic(h),  // ← the harmonic function IS the data
  key.chord(1).asMusic(h),
]);

// The actual music: melody and harmony happening together
final piece = Par([melody, harmony]);

// Now transpose the whole thing to G major — one operation, everything moves
final inG = Transform(piece, Transpose(Interval(IntervalQuality.perfect, 5)));

// Or get the retrograde inversion, because you're writing a fugue
final development = Transform(melody, ComposeTransforms([
  Retrograde(),
  Invert(key.pitch(1, 4)),
]));
```

## Where This Design Gets Interesting (and Where It Breaks)

**What works well**: The `Seq`/`Par`/`Transform` algebra is genuinely compositional — you can nest it arbitrarily deep without the types fighting you. A symphony and a single note are the same type. Transformations are lazy (the `Transform` node doesn't compute anything until you traverse it), so you can represent "this fugue subject, inverted and in augmentation" without generating all the notes upfront.

**What I'm uncertain about**: The tension model. I included it because I believe music-as-data without tension is like language-as-data without semantics — you've captured the syntax but missed the meaning. But tension might be better as a *derived analysis* than as annotations in the data model. The risk of including it: you're mixing objective structure (this IS a C major chord) with subjective interpretation (this chord feels like a 0.7 on the harmonic tension scale). I'd probably start without it and see if the algebra is rich enough to *derive* tension from structure.

**What's deliberately missing**: Timbre/instrumentation. Not because it doesn't matter, but because it's a separate axis. A melody is the same melody whether played by a flute or a cello. The data model above represents what's *invariant* across orchestrations. Timbre would be a parallel annotation layer, not mixed into the music algebra.

**The deepest limitation**: Music has *expectations*. A V7 chord creates tension not because of its acoustic properties but because of everything you've heard before — in this piece, in this genre, in your life. This model captures local harmonic function but not the listener's learned expectations. That's probably a runtime/context concern rather than a data structure concern, but it's where the real musical meaning lives, and I want to be honest that we're not touching it.

The structural analogy that kept guiding me: this is **parser combinators for music**. `Seq` is sequencing, `Par` is parallel choice (well, parallel execution), `Transform` is `map`. The music algebra has the same shape as a monadic parser — which makes sense, because both are about building complex structures from simple composable pieces with a notion of "what comes next."

The bug is in two words you wrote: **"per-operation mutex."**

If each operation gets its own mutex instance, you have N operations each locking their own private lock. Nobody waits for anyone. It's a lock on an unlocked door — structurally present, functionally absent.

Here's what's happening concretely:

```
Operation A: acquire(mutexA) → read(value=5) → check(5 < 10) → write(6) → release(mutexA)
Operation B: acquire(mutexB) → read(value=5) → check(5 < 10) → write(6) → release(mutexB)
```

A and B run concurrently, each holding a *different* mutex. Both read `5`, both write `6`. Duplicate write.

**What you need is a mutex per logical resource**, not per operation. If operations contend on the same database row, they need to share a lock keyed to that row.

```
// Wrong: new mutex per call
Future<void> updateWidget(String id) async {
  final mutex = Mutex();        // ← every caller gets their own
  await mutex.acquire();
  // ...
}

// Right: shared mutex per resource
final _locks = <String, Mutex>{};
Mutex _lockFor(String id) => _locks.putIfAbsent(id, Mutex.new);

Future<void> updateWidget(String id) async {
  final mutex = _lockFor(id);   // ← same id → same mutex
  await mutex.acquire();
  // ...
}
```

**But there's a deeper question you should be asking.** Even after fixing this, you have an in-process lock. If your service runs on more than one instance (multiple pods, containers, replicas), the mutex is worthless again — process A's lock is invisible to process B on another machine. Same bug, different scale.

The real fix depends on which layer you want to enforce consistency:

**Option 1: Push it to the database.** This is almost always the right answer. Replace the check-then-write with an atomic conditional update:

```sql
UPDATE widgets SET counter = counter + 1 WHERE id = ? AND counter < 10;
```

If the affected row count is 0, the condition wasn't met. No read-then-check-then-write. One atomic statement. No lock needed at all. This works across any number of service instances.

**Option 2: Optimistic concurrency.** Add a version column. Read the value and its version, do your check, then write with `WHERE version = ?`. If someone else wrote in between, the update affects 0 rows, and you retry.

```sql
UPDATE widgets SET value = ?, version = version + 1
WHERE id = ? AND version = ?;
```

**Option 3: Distributed lock** (Redis SETNX, database advisory lock, ZooKeeper). Use this only when the logic between read and write is genuinely complex and can't be collapsed into a single SQL statement. It's the most operationally expensive option and introduces its own failure modes (lock holder crashes, lock expires mid-operation, clock skew).

**My strong recommendation:** Option 1 if the condition is expressible in SQL. Option 2 if you need to read, transform in application code, and write back. Option 3 only as a last resort. The in-process mutex (even correctly shared) should be treated as a performance optimization to reduce database contention, never as the source of correctness.

The pattern to be suspicious of: any time you see `read → application logic → write` with a lock around it, ask whether the read and write can be collapsed into a single atomic database operation. If they can, the lock was never solving the right problem — it was compensating for a decomposition that shouldn't exist.

Here's the thing most people get wrong about email validation: they try to solve it with one regex, and that regex is either too permissive (allows `@@@`) or too restrictive (rejects `user+tag@sub.domain.co.uk`), or it's the infamous RFC 5322 regex that's 6,343 characters long and nobody can debug.

The better move is to validate in layers — cheap structural checks first, then progressively finer rules. Written in Dart since that's what this project uses:

```dart
/// Result of email validation — carries *why* it failed, not just that it did.
class EmailValidation {
  final bool isValid;
  final String? reason;

  const EmailValidation.valid() : isValid = true, reason = null;
  const EmailValidation.invalid(this.reason) : isValid = false;

  @override
  String toString() => isValid ? 'Valid' : 'Invalid: $reason';
}

/// Validates an email address for practical use.
///
/// This deliberately does NOT implement the full RFC 5322 spec. Quoted local
/// parts like `"john doe"@example.com` are technically valid but no real mail
/// system expects them. We validate what humans actually type into forms.
EmailValidation validateEmail(String email) {
  // Layer 0: emptiness and whitespace
  final trimmed = email.trim();
  if (trimmed.isEmpty) return const EmailValidation.invalid('empty');
  if (trimmed != email) return const EmailValidation.invalid('leading/trailing whitespace');

  // Layer 1: exactly one @
  final atParts = email.split('@');
  if (atParts.length != 2) {
    return EmailValidation.invalid(
      atParts.length < 2 ? 'missing @' : 'multiple @ characters',
    );
  }

  final [local, domain] = atParts;

  // Layer 2: local part
  if (local.isEmpty) return const EmailValidation.invalid('empty local part');
  if (local.length > 64) return const EmailValidation.invalid('local part exceeds 64 chars');
  if (local.startsWith('.') || local.endsWith('.')) {
    return const EmailValidation.invalid('local part starts/ends with dot');
  }
  if (local.contains('..')) {
    return const EmailValidation.invalid('consecutive dots in local part');
  }

  // Allowed: alphanumeric, dot, hyphen, underscore, plus (for +tagging)
  // This is stricter than RFC but matches what real providers accept.
  final localPattern = RegExp(r'^[a-zA-Z0-9.!#$%&*+/=?^_`{|}~-]+$');
  if (!localPattern.hasMatch(local)) {
    return const EmailValidation.invalid('invalid character in local part');
  }

  // Layer 3: domain
  if (domain.isEmpty) return const EmailValidation.invalid('empty domain');
  if (domain.length > 253) return const EmailValidation.invalid('domain exceeds 253 chars');
  if (domain.startsWith('-') || domain.endsWith('-')) {
    return const EmailValidation.invalid('domain starts/ends with hyphen');
  }
  if (domain.startsWith('.') || domain.endsWith('.')) {
    return const EmailValidation.invalid('domain starts/ends with dot');
  }

  final labels = domain.split('.');
  if (labels.length < 2) {
    return const EmailValidation.invalid('domain has no TLD (missing dot)');
  }

  final labelPattern = RegExp(r'^[a-zA-Z0-9]([a-zA-Z0-9-]*[a-zA-Z0-9])?$');
  for (final label in labels) {
    if (label.isEmpty) return const EmailValidation.invalid('consecutive dots in domain');
    if (label.length > 63) return const EmailValidation.invalid('domain label exceeds 63 chars');
    if (!labelPattern.hasMatch(label)) {
      return EmailValidation.invalid('invalid domain label: "$label"');
    }
  }

  // The TLD must contain at least one letter (blocks `user@123.456`)
  final tld = labels.last;
  if (!RegExp(r'[a-zA-Z]').hasMatch(tld)) {
    return const EmailValidation.invalid('TLD is all-numeric');
  }

  return const EmailValidation.valid();
}
```

The design choices worth noting:

**Returning `EmailValidation` instead of `bool`.** A bare boolean is almost useless to the caller — when validation fails on a form, you need to tell the user *what's wrong*. The reason string is the actual product here, not the boolean.

**No single regex.** Each check is readable, debuggable, and independently testable. When someone reports that `o'malley@example.com` is rejected, you can find the exact line responsible instead of staring at a 200-character regex.

**Deliberately stricter than RFC 5322.** The spec allows things like `"spaces here"@domain` and `(comments)user@domain`. No real user has these. Being permissive about them just lets typos through. The goal isn't spec-compliance — it's catching mistakes while letting real addresses through.

**The TLD-must-have-a-letter check** is one people often miss. `user@192.168.1.1` looks like it could be valid (and technically is for SMTP), but in a user-facing form it's almost certainly a mistake. If you actually need to support IP-literal domains, you'd add a separate branch for `[192.168.1.1]` syntax — but I'd bet against needing it.
